# Text-file line-ending normalization.
#
# We use `text=auto` (not `text=auto eol=lf`) because handwritten source
# files are the only thing we want normalized: CRLF written by a Windows
# IDE → LF in the blob. Consumers on any platform get appropriate local
# line endings on checkout via their `core.autocrlf` setting.
* text=auto

# Explicit binary types — no line-ending conversion, no text diffs.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.pdf binary
*.zip binary
*.tar.gz binary

# Source maps are text but huge and rarely worth diffing line-by-line.
*.map linguist-generated=true

# Generated bundle — treat as binary so git preserves the exact bytes
# ncc produced (including any CRLF from CRLF-bearing bundled deps like
# tslib). This is the canonical fix from
# https://www.aleksandrhovhannisyan.com/blog/crlf-vs-lf-normalizing-line-endings-in-git/
# for "artifacts that should be committed with their tool-produced line
# endings unchanged":
#   - `-text` disables text conversion: no CRLF↔LF rewriting on add or
#     checkout. Bytes stored = bytes on disk, byte-identical across all
#     platforms (macOS dev, Linux CI ARM64, Linux CI x86-64).
#   - `linguist-generated=true` keeps GitHub's PR viewer collapsing the
#     dist/ diff so reviewers aren't walked through 3+ MB of bundle.
# Why this fixes the CI dist-freshness gate: previously, macOS `git add`
# normalized working-tree CRLF to LF in the blob, then CI's rebuild
# produced CRLF bytes again, and `git diff dist/` against the LF blob
# showed 2 "uncommitted changes" (reflected in GitVersion_UncommittedChanges).
# With `-text`, the blob retains CRLF, CI rebuild produces the same CRLF,
# and the diff is empty — no filter asymmetry between local add and CI diff.
dist/** -text linguist-generated=true
